U.S. Leads in Pollution Control Equipment Exports

The U.S. was the world's leading exporter of pollution control
equipment in 1991 with a trade surplus of $1.1 billion according to
a report released by the U.S. Environmental Protection Agency
(EPA).  Germany led in 1990, but U.S. companies took the lead in
1991 with $188 million more in exports than Germany.  U.S.
environmental exports increased 70% from 1989 to 1991, while
imports increased 45%.


